{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":886,"record_hash":"sha256:4243ca0b5ac733f0031576c792488cf3cd3ae2a5c543c2ec36aba31264996b44","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:01:40.424Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n The safer default is: a web/API facade owns the website and JSON API contract; a\n separate generator service owns local repositories, GitMeta materialization,\n `but-agentlog`, and Rust runtime concerns. Revisit putting the generator in the\n web app only after the deployment environment is confirmed to satisfy the\n runtime checklist above.\n+\n+## Filesystem / Cache Architecture\n+\n+The generator needs a real local filesystem. Treat the Git/GitMeta cache as a\n+local working set, not as durable product data.\n+\n+Recommended v1 architecture:\n+\n+```text\n+web/API facade -> generator HTTP API -> one generator process\n+                                  -> one mounted persistent volume\n+```\n+\n+Use object storage only for backups, exported projection JSON, or archived\n+snapshots. Do not try to run the live Git object database or GitMeta SQLite\n+state directly on S3/R2/Tigris-style object storage.\n+\n+Why:\n+\n+- Git repositories expect filesystem behavior: directories, many small files,\n+  atomic renames, file locks, and random reads.\n+- `git-meta-lib` currently materializes state into `.git/git-meta.sqlite` next\n+  to the repository. That also wants a normal local filesystem.\n+- SQLite's WAL documentation says all processes using a database must be on the\n+  same host and WAL does not work over a network filesystem\n+  ([SQLite WAL](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)). Avoid clever shared-network\n+  filesystem designs unless there is a strong reason.\n+\n+Lightweight hosting options that fit:\n+\n+- Fly.io Machine + Fly Volume. Fly volumes are local persistent storage for Fly\n+  Machines and get daily snapshots\n+  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n+- Render background worker or private service + persistent disk. Render supports\n+  disks for paid services and background workers\n+  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n+- Railway service + volume. Railway volumes mount persistent read/write storage\n+  into a service\n+  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n+\n+AWS can solve this, but it is heavier than needed for v1. Lambda/ECS can mount\n+EFS ([Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n+[ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)),\n+but that introduces VPC, mount targets, IAM, throughput modes, network\n+filesystem semantics, and more operational surface. Use it only if the rest of\n+the product is already committed to AWS.\n+\n+Directory layout:\n+\n+```text\n+/var/lib/agent-trail/\n+  repos/\n+    github/\n+      <github-repo-id>/\n+        repo.git/              # preferred if but-agentlog supports bare repos\n+        repo/                  # fallback non-bare repo with no checkout\n+  locks/\n+    github/\n+      <github-repo-id>.lock\n+  db/\n+    agent-trail.sqlite         # optional generator-local job/result index\n+  snapshots/\n+    <snapshot-id>.json         # optional exported projection cache\n+  tmp/\n+```\n+\n+Use numeric GitHub repository ids or opaque hashes for filesystem paths. Keep\n+owner/repo names as display metadata, not path authority.\n+\n+Concurrency model:\n+\n+- Start with one generator process attached to one volume.\n+- Use a per-repository lock around repo initialization, fetch, GitMeta\n+  materialization, and projection.\n+- Do not let multiple generator instances write the same repository cache.\n+- If more capacity is needed, shard repositories across workers by GitHub repo\n+  id, or put generation jobs in a queue and route each repo to one owner worker.\n+- The web/API facade should not mount or inspect the repository volume.\n+\n+Cache policy:\n+\n+- The repository cache is rebuildable from public metadata refs, so it is not\n+  critical durable data.\n+- Generated projections can be regenerated as long as the metadata ref still\n+  exists. Store them for speed and stable user experience, not as the only copy\n+  of evidence.\n+- Keep quotas from day one: max repos, max bytes per repo, total volume high\n+  watermark, LRU eviction, negative-cache TTL for missing metadata, and\n+  per-repo fetch debounce.\n+- Deleting a repository cache must happen under that repo's lock.\n+\n+Backup policy:\n+\n+- For v1, rely on provider volume snapshots plus the fact that repo caches are\n+  rebuildable.\n+- If generator-local SQLite becomes important, add a real SQLite backup path\n+  rather than copying live database files. Litestream can replicate SQLite to\n+  S3-compatible storage ([Litestream](https://litestream.io/getting-started/)).\n+- Do not back up huge live Git caches unless there is measured evidence that\n+  warm-cache loss is painful.\n+\n+This keeps the first production setup small: one container, one volume, one\n+service API, and a rebuildable cache. The escape hatch is straightforward: add\n+object storage for projection exports or backups, then shard generator workers\n+only when load proves it is needed.\n \n ## Online Research Findings (2026-05-24)\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:01:40.424Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}